li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=zUgyq4zpgIU&#x26;feature=youtu.be\">Blazor Train: WebAssembly</a> - <img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/Duration:%20-12%20min-%230094FF?style=flat-square&#x26;cacheSeconds=maxAge&#x26;logo=youtube\" alt=\"duration\"> May 26, 2020 - Blazor Train, episode 3: On this episode of Blazor Train, we’ll dive into WebAssembly. What is it? Is it secure? How does it work? What browsers support it? What languages can compile to it? Can it only run in the browser? And we’ll answer the question: Is Blazor Wasm the next Silverlight?</li>","updatedAt":"2020-06-05T13:29:31.000Z"},{"awesomeListRepo":"AdrienTorris/awesome-blazor","categoryHTML":"<h2>Videos</h2>","itemHTML":"<li><a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=CUJP82uAU5Y&#x26;feature=youtu.be\">Blazor Train: Server vs WASM</a> - <img src=\"https://img.shields.io/badge/Duration:%20-20%20min-%230094FF?style=flat-square&#x26;cacheSeconds=maxAge&#x26;logo=youtube\" alt=\"duration\"> May 26, 2020 - Blazor Train, episode 2: Server vs WASM, by Carl Franklin. In this episode of Blazor Train, he compares the two hosting models: Blazor Server and Blazor WebAssembly. He creates an app using each model, and watch the network traffic in the browser. He talks about the maximum number of concurrent clients a Blazor Server app can handle, and how to scale it to meet demands. Most importantly, he weighs the pros and cons of each hosting model, so you can start thinking about which is appropriate for your next application.</li>","updatedAt":"2020-06-05T13:29:31.000Z"},{"awesomeListRepo":"analysis-tools-dev/static-analysis","categoryHTML":"<h2>Meaning of Symbols:</h2>","itemHTML":"<li>©️ stands for proprietary software. All other tools are Open Source.</li>","updatedAt":"2020-06-05T12:30:51.000Z"},{"awesomeListRepo":"iipc/awesome-web-archiving","categoryHTML":"<h2>Training/Documentation</h2>","itemHTML":"<li>For researchers using web archives:\n<ul>\n<li><a href=\"https://glam-workbench.github.io/web-archives/\">GLAM Workbench: Web Archives</a> - See also <a href=\"https://netpreserveblog.wordpress.com/2020/05/28/asking-questions-with-web-archives/\">this related blog post on 'Asking questions with web archives'</a>.</li>\n<li><a href=\"https://aut.docs.archivesunleashed.org/\">Archives Unleashed Toolkit documentation</a></li>\n</ul>\n</li>","updatedAt":"2020-06-05T10:40:01.000Z"},{"awesomeListRepo":"iipc/awesome-web-archiving","categoryHTML":"<h2>Tools &#x26; Software</h2><h3>Acquisition</h3>","itemHTML":"<li><a href=\"https://github.com/WebMemex\">WebMemex</a> - Browser extension for Firefox and Chrome which lets you archive web pages you visit. <em>(In Development)</em></li>","updatedAt":"2020-06-05T10:40:01.000Z"},{"awesomeListRepo":"iipc/awesome-web-archiving","categoryHTML":"<h2>Community Resources</h2><h3>Other Awesome Lists</h3>","itemHTML":"<li><a href=\"https://github.com/pirate/ArchiveBox/wiki/Web-Archiving-Community\">Web Archiving Community</a></li>","updatedAt":"2020-06-05T10:40:01.000Z"},{"awesomeListRepo":"iipc/awesome-web-archiving","categoryHTML":"<h2>Community Resources</h2><h3>Other Awesome Lists</h3>","itemHTML":"<li><a href=\"https://github.com/machawk1/awesome-memento\">Awesome Memento</a><a data-role=\"trackawesomelist-badge\" href=\"https://github.com/machawk1/awesome-memento\" style=\"text-decoration:none;top: -2px;position: relative;margin-left:4px;margin-right:4px;font-weight:400;\"><span style=\"color: #fff;font-size: 11px;font-family: Verdana, Geneva, DejaVu Sans,sans-serif;\"><span style=\"padding:4px 4px 4px 6px;background: #555;border-top-left-radius: 4px;border-bottom-left-radius: 4px;\">stars</span><span style=\"padding: 4px 6px 4px 4px;background: #007ec6;border-top-right-radius: 4px;border-bottom-right-radius: 4px;\">56</span></span></a><!--TRACK_AWESOME_REPO_ITEM_START____{\"type\":\"repo\",\"stargazerCount\":56,\"repo\":\"machawk1/awesome-memento\"}____TRACK_AWESOME_REPO_ITEM_END--></li>","updatedAt":"2020-06-05T10:40: